# mock-and-test-isolation-patterns — History

## v1.1.0 (2026-05-28)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PR #644 — fixing real test failures across all Python versions
**Verification:** verified-ci (2601 unit tests pass locally; CI triggered on push)

### What changed

- Added trigger (9) to description: stale logger after `importlib.reload`
- Added `When to Use` trigger 9: stale logger object after reload
- Added `### Quick Reference` Pattern 9 code example
- Added `### Pattern 9: Stale Module Reference After importlib.reload` detailed section
- Added `Failed Attempts` row 9 documenting the exact symptom and diagnosis
- Added ProjectHephaestus PR #644 to Verified On table
- Bumped date to 2026-05-28
- Tags: added `importlib-reload`, `stale-reference`, `string-patch`

### Why

Three tests in `test_general_utils.py` failed silently across all Python versions (3.10–3.13):
`test_log_on_error_true_emits_error_log`, `test_long_argv_truncated_in_error_log`,
`test_timeout_expired_is_logged_and_reraised`. All used `patch.object(imported_logger, "error")`.

Root cause: `test_constants.py` calls `importlib.reload(helpers)` inside
`test_metadata_timeout_env_override` and `test_network_timeout_env_override` to test env-var
override of `METADATA_TIMEOUT`/`NETWORK_TIMEOUT`. After reload, `helpers.logger` is a new
`ContextLogger` instance. The `logger` imported at module load time in `test_general_utils.py`
is the old instance. `run_subprocess` uses the new one; the patch targets the old one.

Diagnosis clue: `mock_error.called == False` but the error line appears in captured stdout —
confirming the code executed but via a different object than the mock.

Fix: `patch("hephaestus.utils.helpers.logger.error")` (string form) resolves `helpers.logger`
at patch-entry time, always targeting the current instance.

